pointer->function

primer, ch.9/10

(1) if var in calling func needs to be altered, use pointer to var as arg of called func
    - if called func only needs its val of var for further calculation, transmit var
    - pointers might also be necessary, if callee shall communicate more than one value back
(2) `const` for immutable arrays

EXAMPLE
(1)
int main(void) {
    int x = 5, y = 10;
    printf("Originally x = %d and y = %d.\n", x , y); // x == 5, y == 10
    interchange(&x, &y);
    printf("Now x = %d and y = %d.\n", x, y); // x == 10, y == 5
    return 0;
}
void interchange(int *u, int *v) {
    int temp;
    temp = *u;
    *u = *v;
    *v = temp;
}
(2)
int sum(const int ar[], int n); // prototype

int sum(const int ar[], int n) { // definition
    int total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) total += ar[i];
    return total;
}
